Z-Score (Standard Score) – Data Science Notes

Z-Score is one of the most important statistical concepts in Machine Learning and Data Science. It tells us how far a data point is from the mean, measured in terms of standard deviations.

Definition

A Z-Score indicates the number of standard deviations a value is above or below the mean.

Positive Z-Score → Value is above the mean.
Negative Z-Score → Value is below the mean.
Zero Z-Score → Value is exactly equal to the mean.

formula: Z=  (X − μ​) / σ
Where:

X = Data value
μ (Mu) = Mean
σ (Sigma) = Standard Deviation
Simple Example

Suppose the marks of students are:

40, 50, 60, 70, 80

Mean = 60

Standard Deviation = 10

Find the Z-Score of 80.

Z= (80−60)/10
	​=2

Interpretation:

The student scored 2 standard deviations above the average.

Another Example

Height = 150 cm

Mean = 160 cm

Standard Deviation = 5 cm

Z=(150−160)/5
	​=−2

This means the person's height is 2 standard deviations below the average.

Interpretation Table
Z-Score	Meaning
0	Exactly average
+1	1 Standard Deviation above mean
+2	2 Standard Deviations above mean
-1	1 Standard Deviation below mean
-2	2 Standard Deviations below mean
Why is Z-Score Used?
1. Detect Outliers

A value is usually considered an outlier if:

Z > +3
Z < -3

